===Etymology 1===
From {{der|en|enm|mark}}, {{m|enm|merk}}, {{m|enm|merke}}, from {{der|en|ang|mearc||mark, sign, line of division; standard; boundary, limit, term, border; defined area, district, province}}, from {{der|en|gmw-pro|*marku}}, from {{der|en|gem-pro|*markō||boundary; boundary marker}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*marǵ-||edge, boundary, border}}.

Cognate with {{cog|nl|mark}}, {{m|nl|merk||mark, brand}}, {{cog|de|Mark||mark; borderland}}, {{cog|sv|mark||mark, land, territory}}, {{cog|is|mark||mark, sign}}, {{cog|la|margo||edge, margin}}, {{cog|fa|مرز|4=limit, boundary}}, {{cog|sa|मर्या||limit, mark, boundary}} and {{m|sa|मार्ग||mark, section}}. Compare {{m|en|march}}.

